<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: CYPRESS; SCHOOLS MAY ADOPT BICYCLE HELMET RULE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MIMI KO 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The Cypress School District is considering adopting a policy requiring 
students to wear bicycle helmets while riding to and from school. 
</P>
<P>
 Under the proposed policy, principals would be required to make sure their 
students know they must wear helmets, and teachers would be required to teach 
about bicycle safety. 
</P>
<P>
 Board members said they expect to pass the policy unanimously at their meeting 
on March 8. 
</P>
<P>
 Jeannette Lohrman, principal of Arnold Elementary School, said she supports 
the policy. She told board members last week that a fourth-grade student 
wearing a helmet escaped major head injuries when his bicycle collided with a 
car in the rain outside school on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
 "It works," Lohrman said. "Every kid should have a helmet." 
</P>
<P>
 Parent groups are working with administrators to develop scholarship programs 
to provide helmets for children who cannot afford them, district officials 
said. MIMI KO 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
