<HEADLINE>
<P>
INSIDE JOB: OCCUPATION: RETAIL DISTRICT MANAGER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Name: Carol Yates 
</P>
<P>
 Company: Frederick's of Hollywood 
</P>
<P>
 Thumbs up: "I like getting out to all the stores in my district and seeing 
what is happening in each of them. Most of the customers are there to select 
something for a special occasion, and that makes for a fun day. Frederick's is 
a fun, happy environment, and we sell a fun product. I also like directing our 
employees and working to develop their professional skills." 
</P>
<P>
 Thumbs down: "I spend a lot of time on the road between stores. For some 
people, that might be a drawback. But I have learned to use that time 
constructively. I listen to self-improvement tapes and keep up with the news 
and a little music." 
</P>
<P>
 Next step: "I would like to become a regional manager." 
</P>
<P>
 Advice: "Retail is a very challenging environment. You will succeed according 
to the amount of energy you put into achieving your goals. The ability to keep 
up with current trends is a very strong asset." 
</P>
<P>
 Salary range: $25,000-$65,000 
</P>
<P>
 Hours: "Between 40 to 70 hours a week. During special holidays like 
Valentine's Day and Mother's Day, a district manager will work extra hours, 
including nights and weekends, to make sure everything is going well at the 
stores." 
</P>
<P>
 Educational and training requirements: "Many district managers have a 
bachelor's degree, but it's not required. As you get further along in your 
career, it's your experience that really matters. Most have worked their way up 
through the ranks. Frederick's also places a lot of emphasis on continuing 
education to help their employees develop. We are always learning." 
</P>
<P>
 Job description: "My main responsibility is to help each store in my district 
reach its financial goals. That means maintaining maximum sales volume and 
controlling expenses. I am also in charge of hiring, training and keeping the 
employees motivated." 
</P>
<P>
 Major employing industries: Specialty retail stores. 
</P>
<P>
 For more information: Contact the Fashion Institute of Design and 
Merchandising at (714) 546-0930. 
</P>
<P>
 Researched by JANICE L. JONES / Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</TEXT>
